Datasets and Models.
We use five real-world graph datasets of different scales, i.e.,
Coauthor (Shchur etÂ al. 2018),
Pubmed (Sen etÂ al. 2008), Yelp (Zeng etÂ al. 2019), Reddit (Hamilton etÂ al. 2017), Amazon2M (Hu etÂ al. 2020).
We partition training/ validation sets over 100 clients in both independent and identically distributed (iid) setting and non-iid setting.
We use a non-iid partition by piâˆ¼Dâ€‹iâ€‹rkâ€‹(Î±)similar-tosubscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ·ğ‘–subscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘˜ğ›¼p_{i}\sim Dir_{k}(\alpha), Î±=0.5ğ›¼0.5\alpha=0.5 with a Dirichlet distribution and allocate a pi,ksubscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘˜p_{i,k} ratio of instances of class iğ‘–i to client kğ‘˜k (Li etÂ al. 2022; Yurochkin etÂ al. 2019).
Since the original graph is extremely dense, we downsample the edges in local subgraphs by 50% (Hamilton etÂ al. 2017).
The test dataset is located at the server and the statistics of the datasets are presented in Table 1.
We use the widely adopted GraphSage model (Hamilton etÂ al. 2017) with FedAvg to construct FedGCN models: FedAuthor, FedPubmed, FedYelp, FedReddit, FedAmazon (Hu etÂ al. 2020).
Each model has two hidden layers with 256, 128 neurons.
We set the ratio of sample selection to 0.7, the number of neighbors sampled to 10, and the minimum embedding synchronization interval Ï„0subscriptğœ0\tau_{0} to 2 batch training epochs.
We use Adam as the optimizer with the weight decay 0.001 and ReLU as the activation function.
We set the learning rate Î·=0.001ğœ‚0.001\eta=0.001, the fixed batch number is 10, and the global warm-up round is 1. We conduct training until a pre-specified test accuracy is reached, or a maximum number of iterations has elapsed (e.g., 100 rounds). We perform 5-fold cross validation and report the average results.

FedAIS achieves comparable or higher accuracy.
We adopt three metrics (Falessi etÂ al. 2021; Herbold etÂ al. 2018), i.e., test accuracy, F1-score, and area under the curve (AUC), to evaluate the accuracy of FedGCN models.
We compare FedAIS with other baseline methods by training different FedGCN models in both iid and non-iid settings.
We present the results of those accuracy metric scores and the standard deviations of the final global models in Table 2.
It shows that FedAIS achieves test accuracy, F1 score, and AUC scores that are comparable to or better than other methods. For example, for model FedYelp trained on Yelp dataset in the iid setting, the test accuracy of FedAIS is 4.55%, 3.87%, 5.20%, 5.14 higher than other methods, respectively.
